    {
      "id": "bb_renal2_001",
      "passage": "A nephrology team evaluates patients with acid-base disturbances. Arterial blood gas and urine studies are collected before treatment.\n\nPatient | pH | PCO\u2082 | HCO\u2083\u207b | Urine NH\u2084\u207a\nA | 7.25 | 30 mmHg | 13 mM | high\nB | 7.32 | 60 mmHg | 30 mM | high\nC | 7.52 | 48 mmHg | 38 mM | low\n\nThe team teaches that lungs regulate CO\u2082 rapidly, kidneys regulate bicarbonate and acid excretion more slowly, and compensation usually moves pH toward normal without fully overshooting.",
      "stem": "Patient A's primary disturbance is most consistent with:",
      "choices": [
        {
          "label": "A",
          "text": "metabolic alkalosis"
        },
        {
          "label": "B",
          "text": "respiratory acidosis with renal compensation"
        },
        {
          "label": "C",
          "text": "metabolic acidosis with respiratory compensation"
        },
        {
          "label": "D",
          "text": "normal acid-base status"
        }
      ],
      "correct": "C",
      "explanations": {
        "A": "Metabolic alkalosis would have high pH and elevated bicarbonate, opposite Patient A's data.",
        "B": "Respiratory acidosis would begin with elevated PCO\u2082. Patient A has low PCO\u2082, which is compensatory rather than primary.",
        "C": "Correct. Low pH and low bicarbonate identify primary metabolic acidosis. The low PCO\u2082 reflects hyperventilatory respiratory compensation that helps raise pH toward normal.",
        "D": "The pH is clearly acidemic, so the status is not normal."
      },
      "topic": "Renal Physiology II: Acid-Base & Electrolytes",
      "difficulty": "Medium",
      "passageImage": "data:image/png;base64,"
    },
    {
      "id": "bb_renal2_002",
      "passage": null,
      "stem": "Why is urine NH\u2084\u207a high in Patient A?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "label": "A",
          "text": "Kidneys excrete acid as ammonium during metabolic acidosis"
        },
        {
          "label": "B",
          "text": "Kidneys stop all acid excretion during acidosis"
        },
        {
          "label": "C",
          "text": "NH\u2084\u207a is secreted only in alkalosis"
        },
        {
          "label": "D",
          "text": "Ammonium is a lung gas"
        }
      ],
      "correct": "A",
      "explanations": {
        "A": "Correct. In metabolic acidosis, renal ammoniagenesis and NH\u2084\u207a excretion help remove acid and regenerate bicarbonate. High urine ammonium is an appropriate renal response.",
        "B": "Stopping acid excretion would worsen acidosis. The high NH\u2084\u207a shows the kidney is responding.",
        "C": "Ammonium excretion is especially important in acidosis, not only alkalosis.",
        "D": "Ammonium is handled by renal tubular processes, not exhaled as a primary lung gas."
      },
      "topic": "Renal Physiology II: Acid-Base & Electrolytes",
      "difficulty": "Easy",
      "passageRef": "bb_renal2_001",
      "usePrevPassage": true
    },
    {
      "id": "bb_renal2_003",
      "passage": null,
      "stem": "Patient B most likely has:",
      "choices": [
        {
          "label": "A",
          "text": "metabolic acidosis without compensation"
        },
        {
          "label": "B",
          "text": "respiratory acidosis with metabolic compensation"
        },
        {
          "label": "C",
          "text": "respiratory alkalosis"
        },
        {
          "label": "D",
          "text": "metabolic alkalosis only"
        }
      ],
      "correct": "B",
      "explanations": {
        "A": "Metabolic acidosis would have low bicarbonate as the primary abnormality, not elevated PCO\u2082 with increased bicarbonate.",
        "B": "Correct. Low pH with high PCO\u2082 indicates primary respiratory acidosis. Elevated bicarbonate suggests renal compensation retaining or generating bicarbonate.",
        "C": "Respiratory alkalosis would have low PCO\u2082 and high pH. Patient B has the opposite pattern.",
        "D": "Metabolic alkalosis would have high pH; Patient B remains acidemic."
      },
      "topic": "Renal Physiology II: Acid-Base & Electrolytes",
      "difficulty": "Medium",
