    {
      "id": "bb_renal2_005",
      "passage": null,
      "stem": "Why does compensation usually not overshoot pH past normal?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "label": "A",
          "text": "Compensation reduces the disturbance but does not become a new primary disorder in simple cases"
        },
        {
          "label": "B",
          "text": "The body cannot change CO\u2082 or bicarbonate"
        },
        {
          "label": "C",
          "text": "All compensation is instantaneous and perfect"
        },
        {
          "label": "D",
          "text": "pH is unrelated to PCO\u2082"
        }
      ],
      "correct": "A",
      "explanations": {
        "A": "Correct. Physiologic compensation is a response to the primary disorder and typically moves pH toward normal without creating the opposite pH abnormality. Overshoot suggests mixed disorders or treatment effects.",
        "B": "The body can change CO\u2082 through ventilation and bicarbonate through renal handling.",
        "C": "Compensation differs in speed and is rarely perfect; renal compensation is slower than respiratory compensation.",
        "D": "PCO\u2082 is a major component of the bicarbonate buffer system and strongly affects pH."
      },
      "topic": "Renal Physiology II: Acid-Base & Electrolytes",
      "difficulty": "Medium",
      "passageRef": "bb_renal2_001",
      "usePrevPassage": true
    },
    {
      "id": "bb_renal2_006",
      "passage": "A second experiment measures nephron transporter responses during volume depletion. Low renal perfusion increases renin release, raising angiotensin II and aldosterone. Aldosterone increases sodium reabsorption and potassium secretion in the distal nephron. ADH increases water permeability in collecting ducts. A loop diuretic blocks Na\u207a-K\u207a-2Cl\u207b transport in the thick ascending limb and reduces the medullary osmotic gradient.",
      "stem": "What stimulates renin release during volume depletion?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "label": "A",
          "text": "High distal sodium delivery only"
        },
        {
          "label": "B",
          "text": "Reduced renal perfusion pressure and sympathetic/NaCl signals"
        },
        {
          "label": "C",
          "text": "Excess atrial stretch"
        },
        {
          "label": "D",
          "text": "Complete absence of juxtaglomerular cells"
        }
      ],
      "correct": "B",
      "explanations": {
        "A": "High distal NaCl tends to suppress renin through macula densa signaling rather than stimulate it.",
        "B": "Correct. Low effective circulating volume decreases renal perfusion and activates juxtaglomerular renin release, aided by sympathetic input and macula densa signals. This begins RAAS activation.",
        "C": "Atrial stretch reflects volume expansion and promotes natriuretic responses, not renin release.",
        "D": "Juxtaglomerular cells are required for renin secretion; their absence would impair the response."
      },
      "topic": "Renal Physiology II: Acid-Base & Electrolytes",
      "difficulty": "Medium"
    },
    {
      "id": "bb_renal2_007",
      "passage": null,
      "stem": "Aldosterone most directly increases:",
      "choices": [
        {
          "label": "A",
          "text": "water permeability without ADH"
        },
        {
          "label": "B",
          "text": "proximal glucose filtration only"
        },
        {
          "label": "C",
          "text": "distal sodium reabsorption and potassium secretion"
        },
        {
          "label": "D",
          "text": "bicarbonate destruction in plasma"
        }
      ],
      "correct": "C",
      "explanations": {
        "A": "ADH is the main hormone increasing collecting-duct water permeability through aquaporins.",
        "B": "Glucose filtration is determined mainly by plasma glucose and GFR, not aldosterone's primary action.",
        "C": "Correct. Aldosterone acts on principal cells to increase sodium reabsorption through ENaC and Na\u207a/K\u207a-ATPase activity, promoting potassium secretion. This supports volume retention but can lower serum K\u207a.",
        "D": "Aldosterone does not simply destroy plasma bicarbonate; acid-base effects are more indirect and cell-type dependent."
      },
      "topic": "Renal Physiology II: Acid-Base & Electrolytes",
      "difficulty": "Easy",
      "passageRef": "bb_renal2_006",
      "usePrevPassage": true
    },
    {
      "id": "bb_renal2_008",
      "passage": null,
      "stem": "Why can loop diuretics impair urinary concentration?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "label": "A",
          "text": "They stop glomerular filtration completely"
        },
        {
          "label": "B",
          "text": "They directly add aquaporins to collecting ducts"
        },
        {
          "label": "C",
          "text": "They increase ADH receptor number instantly"
        },
        {
          "label": "D",
          "text": "They reduce the medullary osmotic gradient by blocking thick ascending limb salt reabsorption"
        }
      ],
      "correct": "D",
      "explanations": {
        "A": "Loop diuretics do not stop filtration completely; they alter tubular reabsorption.",
        "B": "Adding aquaporins would increase water reabsorption, but loop diuretics primarily block salt transport upstream.",
        "C": "ADH receptor number is not the acute target of loop diuretics. The concentrating defect comes from loss of medullary hypertonicity.",
        "D": "Correct. The thick ascending limb helps build the medullary gradient by reabsorbing NaCl without water. Blocking NKCC reduces that gradient, making it harder for ADH to concentrate urine."
      },
      "topic": "Renal Physiology II: Acid-Base & Electrolytes",
      "difficulty": "Medium",
      "passageRef": "bb_renal2_006",
      "usePrevPassage": true
    },
    {
      "id": "bb_renal2_009",
      "passage": null,
      "stem": "ADH increases water reabsorption mainly by:",
      "choices": [
        {
          "label": "A",
          "text": "inserting aquaporin-2 channels in collecting ducts"
        },
        {
          "label": "B",
          "text": "blocking all sodium channels in the loop"
        },
        {
          "label": "C",
          "text": "destroying the medulla"
        },
        {
          "label": "D",
          "text": "converting urea into glucose"
        }
      ],
      "correct": "A",
      "explanations": {
        "A": "Correct. ADH promotes aquaporin-2 insertion into the apical membrane of collecting-duct principal cells, allowing water to follow the medullary osmotic gradient.",
        "B": "Loop sodium transport is not ADH's main collecting-duct mechanism.",
        "C": "The medulla must remain hypertonic for ADH to work; destroying it would impair concentration.",
        "D": "Urea recycling can support the gradient, but ADH does not convert urea into glucose."
      },
      "topic": "Renal Physiology II: Acid-Base & Electrolytes",
      "difficulty": "Hard",
      "passageRef": "bb_renal2_006",
      "usePrevPassage": true
    },
    {
      "id": "bb_renal2_010",
      "passage": null,
      "stem": "Volume depletion activates RAAS primarily to:",
      "choices": [
        {
          "label": "A",
          "text": "eliminate aldosterone secretion"
        },
        {
          "label": "B",
          "text": "excrete all sodium immediately"
        },
        {
          "label": "C",
          "text": "restore effective circulating volume and arterial pressure"
        },
        {
          "label": "D",
          "text": "prevent any water reabsorption"
        }
      ],
      "correct": "C",
      "explanations": {
        "A": "Aldosterone is a downstream RAAS effector, not something RAAS eliminates.",
        "B": "Immediate sodium excretion would worsen volume depletion. RAAS favors sodium conservation.",
        "C": "Correct. RAAS increases angiotensin II and aldosterone, supporting vasoconstriction, sodium retention, and water retention. These responses defend effective circulating volume and pressure.",
        "D": "Water reabsorption is generally supported through ADH and sodium retention, not prevented."
      },
      "topic": "Renal Physiology II: Acid-Base & Electrolytes",
      "difficulty": "Medium",
      "passageRef": "bb_renal2_006",
      "usePrevPassage": true
    }
  ]
